      <!-- ── FAQ ── -->
      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              What is the difference between short-term and long-term capital gains?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Short-term capital gains apply when you sell an asset held for one year or less. They are taxed at your ordinary income tax rate, which can be as high as 37%. Long-term capital gains apply to assets held longer than one year and benefit from lower preferential rates of 0%, 15%, or 20% depending on your total taxable income.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              What is the Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT)?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              The NIIT is an additional 3.8% tax on investment income for higher earners. It applies to the lesser of your net investment income or the amount by which your modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) exceeds $200,000 for single filers or $250,000 for married filing jointly. Capital gains count as investment income for NIIT purposes.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              What counts as an improvement when calculating adjusted basis?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Improvements are capital expenditures that add value to the asset or extend its useful life, such as a home addition, new roof, or kitchen remodel. Regular maintenance and repairs do not count. For investments, broker commissions and transaction fees paid at purchase can also be added to your basis.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Can capital losses offset my capital gains?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Yes. Capital losses from selling assets at a loss can offset capital gains dollar for dollar. If your total losses exceed your total gains, you can deduct up to $3,000 of the excess loss against ordinary income per year. Any remaining unused loss carries forward to future tax years indefinitely.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Are crypto and stock gains taxed the same way?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Yes, the IRS treats cryptocurrency as property, not currency. This means crypto gains and losses follow the same short-term and long-term capital gains rules as stocks and real estate. Each sale, exchange, or use of crypto to buy goods or services is a taxable event.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Does this calculator include state capital gains taxes?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              No, this calculator estimates federal capital gains tax only. Most states tax capital gains as ordinary income at the state level. A few states like Texas and Florida have no state income tax. For a full picture, check your state's income tax rate and add it to your federal estimate.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

